Description: THIS PROPOSAL INTENDS TO BUILD ON THE SUCCESS AND PARTNERSHIPS DEVELOPED OVER THE LAST DECADE. THE MEASURE OF SUCCESS IS REFLECTED IN THE NUMBERS OF ACRES BENEFITED DURING THE LAST SEVERAL GRANTS COMPLETED BY CALIFORNIA WATERFOWL AND ITS PARTNERS. IN TOTAL, NAWCA AND PARTICIPATING PARTNER S MATCH DOLLARS HAVE RESTORED 2,619 ACRES OF PALUSTRINE AND ASSOCIATED HABITATS AND A STAGGERING ENHANCEMENT OF 25,613 (1,150) ACRES. AN ADDITIONAL 572 ACRES HAVE BEEN ACQUIRED OR HAVE HAD PERPETUAL CONSERVATION EASEMENTS PUT IN PLACE. THESE PREVIOUSLY FUNDED GRANTS HAVE BEEN SUCCESSFUL DUE TO DEDICATED PARTNERS AND A GREAT WILLINGNESS TO ACCOMPLISH THE GOALS SET OUT WITHIN EACH GRANT.

THIS PROJECT WILL ACQUIRE AND PERMANENTLY PRESERVE 12.7 ACRES AS PART OF THE PARK DISTRICT IN THE TINKERS CREEK WATERSHED HAWTHORN CREEK SUB-WATERSHED. THE PROPERTY CONTAINS A VARIETY OF MESIC AND WET-MESIC HABITATS AND WILL PROVIDE NESTING, ROOSTING, AND FORAGING AREAS FOR MANY BIRDS.

THIS PROPOSAL IMPACTS 88.19 ACRES OF PERMANENTLY PROTECTED HABITAT BY RESTORING 24.9 ACRES OF PALUSTRINE WETLAND HABITAT, ENHANCING 63.3-ACRES OF WETLAND ASSOCIATED UPLANDS. THE HABITAT RESTORATION AND ENHANCEMENT COMPLETED THROUGH THIS PARTNERSHIP EFFORT BENEFITS BREEDING WATERFOWL AND OTHER WILDLIFE ON PERMANENTLY PROTECTED WATERFOWL PRODUCTION AREAS.

THE SNELL CREEK PROJECT WILL PERMANENTLY PROTECT 28 ACRES OF COLD WATER STREAM, WETLANDS AND FORESTS WITH EXCEPTIONAL BIRD, FISH AND WILDLIFE HABITAT VALUES, INCLUDING SEA RUN EASTERN BROOK TROUT, WHICH ARE AN IMPORTANT COMPONENT OF THE WESTPORT RIVER ESTUARY ECOSYSTEM ON BUZZARDS BAY IN SOUTHEASTERN MASSACHUSETTS. THE SUBJECT PROPERTY CONTAINS 700 LINEAR FEET OF STREAM CHANNEL SURROUNDED BY ASSOCIATED WETLANDS AND BACKED BY BUFFERING RIPARIAN FORESTS THAT ARE CRITICAL TO A NUMBER OF WATER-DEPENDENT BIRD SPECIES AS WELL AS ONE OF THE FEW REMAINING VIABLE SEA RUN EASTERN BROOK TROUT POPULATIONS AND TO THE MAINTENANCE OF HABITAT QUALITY IN THE ESTUARY IMMEDIATELY DOWNSTREAM. THE PROJECT LAND (IN THE TOWN OF WESTPORT, BRISTOL COUNTY) IS LOCATED UPSTREAM OF THE EAST BRANCH OF THE WESTPORT RIVER AND IS ADJACENT TO A GROWING BLOCK OF PERMANENTLY PROTECTED CONSERVATION LAND ALONG ANGELINE BROOK AND SNELL CREEK (BOTH BROOK TROUT COLD STREAMS). THE PROJECT INVOLVES THE ACQUISITION OF A CONSERVATION EASEMENT BY BUZZARDS BAY COALITION (REFERRED TO AS A CONSERVATION RESTRICTION IN MASSACHUSETTS) OVER A 28 ACRE PARCEL THROUGH WHICH SNELL CREEK RUNS, THEREBY PROVIDING PERMANENT PROTECTION TO THE CRITICAL HABITATS AND PREVENTING LAND USE CONVERSION. IF AWARDED, THE GRANT FUNDS WILL BE MATCHED 1:1 BY FUNDS RAISED BY THE COALITION. THIS WILL BE AN IMPORTANT EXPANSION OF A PARTNERSHIP OF PEER LAND CONSERVATION ORGANIZATIONS AND THE TOWN OF WESTPORT ALL WORKING TO PROTECT THE WESTPORT RIVER ESTUARY AND ITS ASSOCIATED SEA RUN BROOK TROUT STREAMS AND BUILDS UPON THE EXCEPTIONAL PARTNERSHIP WITH NAWCA TO PROTECT THE IMPORTANT REMAINING WETLAND HABITATS AROUND BUZZARDS BAY. THIS IS PART OF A LARGER PARTNERSHIP EFFORT TO SPECIFICALLY PROTECT THE HABITAT QUALITY OF THE WESTPORT RIVER ESTUARY BY PROTECTING THE STREAM CORRIDORS AND WETLAND COMPLEXES ASSOCIATED WITH THE COLD WATER TRIBUTARIES, INCLUDING SNELL CREEK, OF THIS ESTUARINE ECOSYSTEM.

THROUGH THE ACQUISITION IN FEE OF A REMARKABLE 1,410-ACRE PROPERTY IN RUSSELL, NY, NORTHEAST WILDERNESS TRUST (NEWT) WILL CREATE THE GRASSE RIVER WILDERNESS PRESERVE. NEWT IS CONTRACTED TO PURCHASE THE PROPERTY AT THE END OF AUGUST 2022, AT WHICH POINT IT WILL BE PLACED UNDER A FOREVER-WILD CONSERVATION EASEMENT HELD BY THE ST. LAWRENCE LAND TRUST TO ENSURE THE PROPERTY S PERMANENT PROTECTION AS WILDERNESS. THE CREATION OF THE GRASSE RIVER WILDERNESS PRESERVE WILL ALLOW THIS PROPERTY S WETLAND AND OTHER HABITATS TO RECOVER FROM PAST DISTURBANCES, REWILD, AND MATURE, RESULTING IN NUMEROUS ECOLOGICAL BENEFITS, THE MOST NOTABLE OF WHICH WILL INCLUDE: HABITAT RESTORATION AND PROTECTION FOR THE PROPERTY S WETLAND AND STREAM ECOSYSTEMS, BUFFERING FOREST, AND OTHER HABITATS, RESULTING IN INCREASED BIODIVERSITY  PREVENTION OF SOIL EROSION AND IMPROVEMENT OF WATER QUALITY IN THE GRASSE RIVER AND ITS TRIBUTARIES  INCREASED POTENTIAL CARBON SEQUESTRATION IN THE PROPERTY S FOREST  PERMANENT PROTECTION OF ONE OF THE FEW STABLE POPULATIONS OF THE EASTERN PEARLSHELL MUSSEL IN NEW YORK STATE  AND THE EXPANSION OF A LOCAL NETWORK OF PROTECTED LANDS, WHICH WILL PROMOTE LANDSCAPE CONNECTEDNESS ACROSS THE REGION. MORE SPECIFICALLY, THIS PROPERTY SHARES A 1.5-MILE BOUNDARY WITH ADIRONDACK PARK, THE LARGEST SINGLE PROTECTED REGION FOUND IN THE LOWER 48 STATES AT 6.1 MILLION ACRES. APPROXIMATELY HALF OF THE LAND WITHIN THE PARK IS STATE-OWNED, WHILE THE REST IS PRIVATELY OWNED BUT SUBJECT TO SUCH REGULATIONS AS TO MAINTAIN THE INTEGRITY AND CONDITION OF THE REGION AS A GENERALLY WILD STATE. THE PROPERTY ALSO ADJOINS DOWNERVILLE AND DEGRASSE STATE FORESTS TO THE NORTH AND SOUTH, WHICH TOGETHER COMPRISE OVER 2,5000 ACRES OF GAP 3 PROTECTED LAND. WITHIN THIS ALREADY WELL-CONNECTED LANDSCAPE, THE ADDITION OF A 1,410-ACRE CORE WILDERNESS AREA WILL BE OF SIGNIFICANT BENEFIT FOR MANY MIGRATORY SPECIES.

THE ROCKY RIVER BOTTOMLANDS ARE A SIGNIFICANT PROJECT FOR THREE RIVERS LAND TRUST. THIS FEE ACQUISITION PROJECT ENCOMPASSES 110 ACRES AND OVER 7,600 FEET OF STREAM FRONTAGE ALONG THE ROCKY RIVER AND UNNAMED TRIBUTARIES. OF THE 110 ACRES IN THE PROJECT, 16.2 ACRES ARE DESIGNATED AS WETLANDS BY THE NATIONAL WETLANDS INVENTORY. THESE ECOSYSTEMS ARE DIRECTLY CORRELATED TO SIGNIFICANT DECLINING HABITAT TYPES FOR BOTH MIGRATORY SPECIES AND RESIDENT POPULATIONS OF WILDLIFE.

MARCH ISLAND RANCH (MIR) LIES IN THE LOWER KLAMATH BASIN (KB) AND IS WITHIN THE HEART OF THE SOUTHERN OREGON AND NORTHEASTERN CALIFORNIA (SONEC) REGION. THE PROPOSED PROJECT WILL EFFECTIVELY ENHANCE AND PROTECT 65 ACRES OF SEASONAL WETLAND HABITAT THAT DIRECTLY ABUTS THE LOWER KLAMATH NATIONAL WILDLIFE REFUGES. EFFORTS WILL BE FOCUSED ON REBUILDING LEVEES, REPLACING DILAPIDATED WATER CONTROL INFRASTRUCTURE. THE PROJECT WILL ENHANCE RESOURCES UTILIZED BY HIGH PRIORITY WATERFOWL SPECIES, PRIORITY WATERFOWL SPECIES, AND OTHER SPECIES OF WATERFOWL.

THE POUPARD BAY PROTECTION PROJECT S GOAL IS TO PERMANENTLY PROTECT 22 ACRES WITH 950 FEET OF FRONTAGE ALONG LAKE MICHIGAN WEST OF ST. IGNACE IN MACKINAC COUNTY, MICHIGAN. THIS PROPOSAL PRESENTS DUCKS UNLIMITED, INC. S SECOND LONG-TERM COMPREHENSIVE EFFORT TO CONSERVE WETLANDS AND WETLAND-DEPENDENT MIGRATORY BIRD POPULATIONS IN THE HONEY LAKE SUB-BASIN WITHIN THE SOUTHERN OREGON NORTHEAST CALIFORNIA (SONEC) WETLAND BASINS. SONEC IS ONE OF THE AREAS OF GREATEST CONTINENTAL SIGNIFICANCE TO NORTH AMERICAN WATERFOWL AS IDENTIFIED BY THE NORTH AMERICAN WATERFOWL MANAGEMENT PLAN (NAWMP) AND IS ONE OF THE TOP PRIORITIES OF THE INTERMOUNTAIN WEST JOINT VENTURE (IWJV). THE PROPOSAL FOCUSES ON PROTECTION AND ENHANCEMENT OF 1,601 (482) ACRES OF PALUSTRINE EMERGENT WETLANDS (PEM) DUE TO THEIR VERY HIGH VALUE TO FALL AND SPRING MIGRATING WATERFOWL, WATERBIRDS AND SHOREBIRDS IN THE REGION.FIVE MILLION DABBLING DUCKS, INCLUDING 2.4 MILLION NORTHERN PINTAILS DEPEND ON SONEC FOR SPRING MIGRATIONS WITH UP TO 70  OF THE PACIFIC FLYWAY MIGRANTS STAGING IN SONEC. SPRING GOOSE POPULATIONS IN SONEC EXCEED 500,000 BIRDS, 200,000 OF WHICH ARE PACIFIC GREATER WHITE-FRONTED GEESE. NEARLY 70,000 TUNDRA SWANS MIGRATE THROUGH SONEC AS WELL. BEYOND ITS MIGRATION ROLE, SONEC SUPPORTS 20  OF NORTH AMERICA S ENTIRE BREEDING POPULATION OF CINNAMON TEAL AND 18  OF THE PACIFIC FLYWAY S POPULATION OF BREEDING MALLARDS AND REDHEADS. THE SONEC REGION ALSO PROVIDES SIGNIFICANT HABITAT FOR MIGRATING AND NESTING SHOREBIRDS AND WATERBIRDS, AND BECAUSE OF ITS IMPORTANCE TO BREEDING AND MIGRATING WETLAND DEPENDENT BIRD POPULATION IN THE PACIFIC FLYWAY, THE PROJECT AREA COVERS REGIONS IDENTIFIED AS CONTINENTAL PRIORITY AREAS FOR ALL FOUR MAJOR BIRD PLANS.GRANT, MATCH, AND NON-MATCH WORK WILL IMPROVE WATER CONVEYANCE AND DISTRIBUTION THEREBY IMPROVING WATER MANAGEMENT CAPABILITIES FURTHER ENHANCING THE PRODUCTION OF INVERTEBRATES, AND AQUATIC AND MOIST SOIL VEGETATION, ALL OF WHICH PROVIDE IMPORTANT FOOD FOR WATERFOWL, WATERBIRDS, AND SHOREBIRDS THROUGHOUT THE ANNUAL CYCLE, AND MOST NOTABLY DURING SPRING MIGRATION. THIS WORK INCLUDES INSTALLING FISH SCREEN AND FISH PASSAGE STRUCTURES WHICH WILL CONTINUE TO ALLOW FLOOD IRRIGATION ON AN IMPORTANT WET MEADOW SYSTEM, RECONTOURING THE LAND AND CREATING ISLANDS WITHIN A SEMI-PERMANENT WETLAND, RECONSTRUCTING EXISTING LOW LEVEES AND INSTALLING NEW WATER CONTROL STRUCTURES TO IMPROVE MANAGEMENT ON A STATE WILDLIFE AREA, CONSTRUCTING ROCK WEIRS AND PREVENTING FURTHER EROSION IN A WET MEADOW SYSTEM, AND UPGRADING WATER DELIVERY STRUCTURES ON A STATE WILDLIFE AREA.THE PROJECT BRINGS TOGETHER AND OUTSTANDING PARTNERSHIP TO PROTECT, AND ENHANCE 3,301 (489) PEM WETLANDS, PFO WETLANDS, AND ASSOCIATED UPLANDS IN THIS CONTINENTALLY IMPORTANT REGION. IT INCLUDES NINE TOTAL PARTNERS, FOUR 10  PARTNERS, FOUR NEW PARTNERS, AND REPRESENTATIVES FROM SIX PARTNER CATEGORIES.

MID-ATLANTIC BLACKWATERS AND BAYS I IS THE FIRST ITERATION IN A POSSIBLE SERIES OF FUTURE PROPOSALS PLANNED BY DUCKS UNLIMITED IN CONJUNCTION WITH STATE AND FEDERAL AGENCIES, PRIVATE CORPORATIONS, AND CONSERVATION-MINDED PRIVATE LANDOWNERS TO PROTECT, RESTORE, AND ENHANCE PRIORITY WETLANDS ON BOTH PRIVATE AND PUBLIC LANDS THROUGHOUT NORTHEASTERN NORTH CAROLINA AND SOUTHEASTERN VIRGINIA. THE EMPHASIS OF THIS PROPOSAL ON BLACKWATER RIVERS AND COASTAL BAYS OF THE MID-ATLANTIC IS INSPIRED BY THE SIGNIFICANCE OF THE WATERWAYS AND WATERSHEDS WITHIN THE REGION AND THE IMPORTANCE OF PREVENTING THE OVER-DEVELOPMENT OF THE AREA, WHILE REDUCING NON-POINT SOURCE POLLUTION, RESTORING CLEAN WATER, RECOVERING HABITAT, AND SUSTAINING ENVIRONMENTAL AND HABITAT RESOURCES FOR MIGRATORY WATERFOWL, OTHER WILDLIFE, AND THE PUBLIC IN THE REGION.

THIS PROPOSAL WILL PROTECT AND RESTORE VALUABLE HABITAT IN AN AREA CONSIDERED ONE OF THE WORLD S MOST BIOLOGICALLY PRODUCTIVE ENVIRONMENTS, THE GULF OF MAINE ECOSYSTEM. THE MAINE WETLANDS CONSERVATION INITIATIVE (MWCI) WAS FORMED IN 2018, SPEARHEADED BY THE APPLICANT MAINE COAST HERITAGE TRUST, TO ENGAGE DIVERSE CONSERVATION PARTNERS FROM ACROSS MAINE AND TARGET PROJECTS OF HIGHEST CONSERVATION IMPACT. THE COALITION HAS SINCE GROWN INTO A GROUP OF MORE THAN 30 MATCHING PARTNERS CONTRIBUTING OVER  42.7 MILLION IN MATCH AGAINST  13 MILLION IN REQUESTED GRANT FUNDS. THIS PHASE III PROPOSAL BUILDS ON THE SUCCESSES OF MAINE WETLANDS CONSERVATION INITIATIVE I AND II, AND WILL ADD 2,324.7 ACRES OF PERMANENTLY PROTECTED OR RESTORED WETLANDS AND SURROUNDING UPLAND BUFFERS TO OVER 4.2 MILLION PROTECTED ACRES IN THE PROPOSAL AREA, INCLUDING NEARLY 500,000 ACRES OF CONSERVED WETLANDS. THE MAINE WETLANDS CONSERVATION INITIATIVE III PROPOSAL INCLUDES ACTIVITIES IN CUMBERLAND, OXFORD, SAGADAHOC, WASHINGTON AND YORK COUNTIES, MAINE.PROPOSAL ACTIVITIES INCLUDE 5 ACQUISITIONS AND 1 HABITAT RESTORATION PROJECT IN THE FOLLOWING ECOLOGICALLY RICH AREAS OF MAINE: 1) DOWNEAST MAINE, A LONGSTANDING CONTINENTAL STRONGHOLD FOR AMERICAN BLACK DUCK, PROVIDING ICE-FREE SHELTERED WINTERING HABITAT IN CLOSE PROXIMITY TO QUALITY BREEDING AREAS AS WELL AS HOSTING TENS OF THOUSANDS OF SHOREBIRDS DURING ANNUAL MIGRATION. THIS PROPOSAL WILL PROTECT THE ENTIRE SHORE OF 12.3-ACRE WESTERN LAKE, A PUBLICLY OWNED GREAT POND UN MAINE LAW, AS WELL AS ACQUIRE A COASTAL TRACT IN AN ACJV FOCUS AREA FOR BREEDING NELSON S SHARP-TAILED SPARROW. 2) KENNEBEC ESTUARY AND MERRYMEETING BAY - A GLOBALLY-UNUSUAL ENCLOSED INLAND DELTA FORMED BY 6 DIFFERENT RIVERS, CONTAINING  20  OF MAINE S TIDAL MARSHES, AND ONE OF THE PREMIER WATERFOWL STAGING GROUNDS ON THE ATLANTIC FLYWAY, HISTORICALLY SUPPORTING  40,000 DUCKS EACH FALL. THIS PROPOSAL WILL PROTECT BREEDING HABITAT IN THE TOP 10  IN RANGE-WIDE SIGNIFICANCE TO SALTMARSH SHARP-TAILED SPARROW AND PROTECT STATE-DESIGNATED ESSENTIAL HABITAT FOR PIPING PLOVER AND LEAST TERN ADJACENT TO A STATE PARK AND STATE WILDLIFE MANAGEMENT AREA. 3) THE PRESUMPSCOT RIVER SUB-BASIN, CONNECTING MAINE S WESTERN FOOTHILLS REGION TO CASCO BAY. THE REGION INCLUDES THE WATERSHED OF 30,000-ACRE SEBAGO LAKE - WITH OUTSTANDING WATER QUALITY AND PROVIDING DRINKING WATER TO 1 6TH OF THE STATE S POPULATION - AND ITS MAIN OUTLET, PRESUMPSCOT RIVER. PROPOSAL ACQUISITIONS IN THE REGION INCLUDE PROTECTION OF ONE OF THE STATE S LARGEST INLAND ROOKERIES FOR MAINE SPECIAL CONCERN SPECIES GREAT BLUE HERON AND THE PROTECTION OF A NEARLY 1,300-ACRE TRACT THAT INCLUDES EXTENSIVE FRESHWATER WETLANDS IN A FORESTED LANDSCAPE CONTEXT. 4) SOUTHERN COASTAL MAINE, INCLUDING RACHEL CARSON NATIONAL WILDLIFE REFUGE, DOMINATED BY SALT MARSHES AND ESTUARIES DOTTED ALONG 50 MILES OF COASTLINE CONTAINING A COLLECTION OF DIVERS HABITATS THAT TOGETHER SUPPORT A COMPOSITION OF SPECIES NOT SEEN ELSEWHERE IN THE STATE. THIS PROPOSAL INCLUDES THE RESTORATION OF VITAL BREEDING HABITAT FOR SALTMARSH SHARP-TAILED SPARROW ON A LONG-TERM MONITORING SITE WHERE BREEDING BIRDS ARE IN SIGNIFICANT DECLINE DUE TO NEST FLOODING.

THIS PROJECT BUILDS UPON THE EFFORT TO RESTORE HYDROLOGICAL FUNCTION IN GREEN TREE RESERVOIRS (GTRS) AND MOIST-SOIL UNITS (MSUS) ON STATE-OWNED LANDS ACROSS THE STATE.
